g in the "Procedural Novel" -- t16. Was noch kein Auge je gesehn: A Spurious Cranach in Georg Georg Kaiser's Von Morgens bis Mitternachts -- tPart Four. Comparative Perspectives on Current Critical Issues -- t17. The Curtain Half Drawn: Prereading in Flaubert and Kafka -- t18. The Modern Lyric: Generic Continuity and Critical Practice -- t19. Kafka and the Sirens: Writing as Lethetic Reading -- t20. Culture Criticism and "Language as Such" -- t21. On the Superficiality of Women -- t22. On the Sign Systems of Biography -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew would deny that comparative literature is rapidly moving from the periphery toward the center of literary studies in North America, but many are still unsure just what it is. The Comparative Perspective on Literature shows by means of twenty-two exemplary essays by many of the most distinguished scholars in the field how comparative literature as a discipline is conceived of and practiced in the 1980s.Nearly all of them published here for the first time, the essays discuss and themselves reflect significant changes at the core of the field as well as evolving notions as to what comparative literature is and should be. The volume editors, Clayton Koelb and Susan Noakes, have included essays that address the scope and concerns of comparative literature today, historical and international contexts of the field, and the relationship of literary criticism to other disciplines, as well as affording comparative perspectives on current critical issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aComparative literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAldridge, A. Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/